<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-124-276 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 929 330</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 24 1991 v37 n1866 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Other distributors skeptical Arrow can keep Big Three. (ArrowElectronics Inc.) (Motorola, Texas Instruments and NationalSemiconductor)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grund, Howard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Industry analysts suspect that semiconductor distributor Arrowwill not be able to keep the combination of Motorola Inc, NationalSemiconductor Corp and Texas Instruments Inc products under itsroof.andP;  Observers note that the big three semiconductormanufacturers have traditionally frowned upon using the samedistributor and that if they allowed Arrow to maintain the threecompetitive lines, the nature of the distribution market wouldchange.andP;  Some believe that the semiconductor manufacturers willnot rush to eliminate Arrow as their distributor because of theeconomic climate in Jun 1991, but Arrow will eventually have tosuffer the loss of at least one of those suppliers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Motorola Inc. (Distribution)National Semiconductor Corp. (Distribution)Texas Instruments Inc. (Distribution)Arrow Electronics Inc. (Distribution).andO;Ticker:    MOT; TXN; NSM; ARW.andO;Topic:     DistributorsSemiconductor industryDistribution AgreementsBusiness PlanningDistribution Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>